            <abstract id="ref10" label="Abstract">The Polonia Paderewski Choir was established in 1952 in New Britain, Connecticut and it was a secular choir with 45 singers. Over the decades the choir performed during national and international competitions. The materials in this collection consists of correspondence, minutes, membership, financial data and photographs, and covers years 1952-1963, and 1969-2004.</abstract>
            <origination label="creator">
                <corpname rules="dacs" source="local">Polonia Paderewski Choir.</corpname>
            </origination>
        </did>
        <scopecontent id="ref8">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The collections consists of scrapbooks/chronicles of choir activities covering years from 1952-1963 and from 1969-2004. Each scrapbook has correspondence, programs, announcements, and minutes of meetings, lists of members, financial data and photographs.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <bioghist id="ref1">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Polonia Paderewski Choir was established in 1952 in New Britain, Connecticut. From the very beginning the group was active and performed in many local Polish and Polish American events. The first chorus was composed of 45 singers: 30 men and 15 women. The chorus’s first public debut was on May 3rd 1952, at the Bushnell memorial in Hartford. In 1952 the chorus was officially named “Polonia” Paderewski Chorus, New Britain, CT, and in the same year they became a part of the Polish Singers Alliance of America, Group 287.</p>
            <p>The “Polonia” Paderewski Chorus has contributed to charitable causes throughout its history and annual December charity concerts became a tradition for the chorus.</p>
            <p>Over the decades the choir participated in many national and international competitions and performed in different venous. In 2015 the choir performed in the St. Patrick’s Cathedral in NYC to commemorate anniversary of death of the Pope John Paul II. More information about the current activities of the choir can be found at: https://poloniapaderewski.wordpress.com/home/english/</p>
        </bioghist>
